===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|chivalrie|lang=enm}}, a late 13th century loan from  {{etyl|fro|en}} word {{term|chevalerie|lang=fro}}, "knighthood, chivalry, nobility, cavalry" (11th century), the ''[[-erie]]''  abstract  of {{term|chevaler|lang=fro}} "knight, horseman", from  {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|caballarius||horseman, knight|lang=la}}, a derivation from  {{term|caballus||horse|lang=la}}.
{{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|caballaria||knighthood, status or fief of a knight|lang=la}} dates to the 12th century.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈʃɪvəlri/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"SIv@lri/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|chivalries}}

# {{context|now|_|rare|historical}} [[cavalry|Cavalry]]; horsemen armed for battle.
#* '''1999''', {{w|George RR Martin}}, ''A Clash of Kings'', Bantam 2011, p. 529:
#*: ‘Most of the lords who rode with Lord Renly to Storm's End have gone over banner-and-blade to Stannis, with all their '''chivalry'''.’
# {{obsolete}} The fact or condition of being a [[knight]]; knightly skill, prowess.
# The ethical code of the [[knight]] prevalent in Medieval [[Europe]], having such primary virtues as [[mercy]] towards the poor and oppressed, [[humility]], [[honor]], [[sacrifice]], fear of [[God]], [[faithfulness]], [[courage]] and utmost [[graciousness]] and [[courtesy]] to ladies.
# Courtesy, respect and honorable conduct between opponents in wartime.
# Courteous behavior, especially that of men towards women.

